Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: My intuition stems from the persistent challenge in implicit discourse relation (IDR) classification: the ambiguity and lack of explicit connectives between discourse units make models highly sensitive to context misinterpretation, especially when training data is sparse or imbalanced. While re-anchoring strategies help realign model focus during inference, they often operate in isolation and lack mechanisms for self-correction or hierarchical knowledge transfer. Drawing inspiration from Paper 1’s multi-granularity interaction, Paper 2’s structured reasoning via Chain-of-Thoughts (CoT), and Paper 3’s hierarchical correlation refinement, I propose a novel framework that *orchestrates* iterative re-anchoring with hierarchical transfer learning and interactive attention—not just as parallel components, but as dynamically interacting modules within a self-correcting loop. The key differentiator lies in the *feedback-driven evolution* of attention weights and feature representations through multiple re-anchoring cycles, where each cycle leverages transferred meta-knowledge from related tasks (via hierarchical transfer) and generates interpretable reasoning traces (via interactive attention). Unlike prior work that treats re-anchoring as a one-off adjustment or uses transfer learning statically, our approach enables the model to iteratively refine its understanding by detecting weak confidence regions, triggering re-evaluation with enriched contextual cues, and updating internal states using distilled insights from source tasks. Furthermore, the integration of interactive attention allows human-in-the-loop validation or synthetic feedback simulation during training, enhancing robustness against noisy or adversarial inputs. This creates a system capable not only of accurate classification but also of explainable, adaptive reasoning—bridging symbolic interpretability with deep learning scalability.

